The paper deals with the problem of computing equilibria in Arrow-Debreu exchange markets, which is a central topic in computational game theory (cs.GT). The algorithm proposed in the paper relies on a demand oracle, which suggests a connection to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also introduces new tools and insights for dealing with precision and representation of prices and demands, which could be of interest to researchers in data structures (cs.DS) and optimization (cs.LG). Finally, the paper is concerned with the computational complexity of the problem, which is a central topic in computational economics (cs.EC).
